JavaScript Conditional Statements (Notes)

Definition
Conditional statements are used to execute code based on conditions.

1. if Statement
Executes code only when condition is true.

Syntax:

if (condition) {
  // code
}


Example:

if (age >= 18) {
  console.log("Eligible to vote");
}

2. if–else Statement

Executes one block if condition is true.

Executes another block if condition is false.

if (condition) {
  // true block
} else {
  // false block
}

3. if–else if–else

Used for multiple conditions.

Conditions are checked top to bottom.

if (marks >= 90) {
  grade = "A";
} else if (marks >= 60) {
  grade = "B";
} else {
  grade = "C";
}

4. switch Statement

Used when multiple fixed values are possible.

break prevents fall-through.

switch (expression) {
  case value1:
    // code
    break;
  case value2:
    // code
    break;
  default:
    // code
}

5. Ternary Operator

Short form of if–else.

Syntax:

condition ? trueValue : falseValue;


Example:

let result = (age >= 18) ? "Adult" : "Minor";

Operators Used in Conditions
Comparison Operators

== Equal (value)

=== Equal (value + type)

!= Not equal

!== Not equal (value + type)

> < >= <=

Logical Operators

&& AND
|| OR
! NOT

Important Points ⭐

Conditions return Boolean value (true / false)
=== is preferred over ==
switch is faster for multiple fixed cases
Use proper indentation for readability

Summary

Conditional statements control program flow
Common types: if, if–else, else if, switch, ternary
